{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Well, as Chris pointed out, I study the human brain,"},{"time":4000,"text":"the functions and structure of the human brain."},{"time":6000,"text":"And I just want you to think for a minute about what this entails."},{"time":10000,"text":"Here is this mass of jelly, three-pound mass of jelly"},{"time":14000,"text":"you can hold in the palm of your hand,"},{"time":17000,"text":"and it can contemplate the vastness of interstellar space."},{"time":21000,"text":"It can contemplate the meaning of infinity"},{"time":23000,"text":"and it can contemplate itself contemplating on the meaning of infinity."},{"time":28000,"text":"And this peculiar recursive quality that we call self-awareness,"},{"time":33000,"text":"which I think is the holy grail of neuroscience, of neurology,"},{"time":37000,"text":"and hopefully, someday, we'll understand how that happens."}]},{"cues":[{"time":40000,"text":"OK, so how do you study this mysterious organ?"},{"time":43000,"text":"I mean, you have 100 billion nerve cells,"},{"time":47000,"text":"little wisps of protoplasm, interacting with each other,"},{"time":50000,"text":"and from this activity emerges the whole spectrum of abilities"},{"time":54000,"text":"that we call human nature and human consciousness."},{"time":57000,"text":"How does this happen?"},{"time":58000,"text":"Well, there are many ways of approaching the functions of the human brain."},{"time":61000,"text":"One approach, the one we use mainly,"},{"time":64000,"text":"is to look at patients with sustained damage to a small region of the brain,"},{"time":69000,"text":"where there's been a genetic change in a small region of the brain."},{"time":71000,"text":"What then happens is not an across-the-board reduction"},{"time":75000,"text":"in all your mental capacities,"},{"time":77000,"text":"a sort of blunting of your cognitive ability."},{"time":80000,"text":"What you get is a highly selective loss of one function,"},{"time":83000,"text":"with other functions being preserved intact,"},{"time":85000,"text":"and this gives you some confidence in asserting"},{"time":87000,"text":"that that part of the brain is somehow involved in mediating that function."},{"time":91000,"text":"So you can then map function onto structure,"},{"time":93000,"text":"and then find out what the circuitry's doing"},{"time":96000,"text":"to generate that particular function."},{"time":98000,"text":"So that's what we're trying to do."}]},{"cues":[{"time":100000,"text":"So let me give you a few striking examples of this."},{"time":103000,"text":"In fact, I'm giving you three examples, six minutes each, during this talk."},{"time":107000,"text":"The first example is an extraordinary syndrome called Capgras syndrome."},{"time":111000,"text":"If you look at the first slide there,"},{"time":113000,"text":"that's the temporal lobes, frontal lobes, parietal lobes, OK --"},{"time":118000,"text":"the lobes that constitute the brain."},{"time":120000,"text":"And if you look, tucked away inside the inner surface of the temporal lobes --"},{"time":124000,"text":"you can't see it there --"},{"time":126000,"text":"is a little structure called the fusiform gyrus."},{"time":128000,"text":"And that's been called the face area in the brain,"},{"time":131000,"text":"because when it's damaged, you can no longer recognize people's faces."},{"time":134000,"text":"You can still recognize them from their voice"},{"time":136000,"text":"and say, \"Oh yeah, that's Joe,\""},{"time":138000,"text":"but you can't look at their face and know who it is, right?"},{"time":141000,"text":"You can't even recognize yourself in the mirror."},{"time":143000,"text":"I mean, you know it's you because you wink and it winks,"},{"time":146000,"text":"and you know it's a mirror,"},{"time":148000,"text":"but you don't really recognize yourself as yourself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":151000,"text":"OK. Now that syndrome is well known as caused by damage to the fusiform gyrus."},{"time":155000,"text":"But there's another rare syndrome, so rare, in fact,"},{"time":158000,"text":"that very few physicians have heard about it, not even neurologists."},{"time":162000,"text":"This is called the Capgras delusion,"},{"time":164000,"text":"and that is a patient, who's otherwise completely normal,"},{"time":167000,"text":"has had a head injury, comes out of coma,"},{"time":170000,"text":"otherwise completely normal, he looks at his mother"},{"time":173000,"text":"and says, \"This looks exactly like my mother, this woman,"},{"time":176000,"text":"but she's an impostor."},{"time":178000,"text":"She's some other woman pretending to be my mother.\""},{"time":180000,"text":"Now, why does this happen?"},{"time":182000,"text":"Why would somebody -- and this person is perfectly lucid and intelligent"},{"time":185000,"text":"in all other respects, but when he sees his mother,"},{"time":187000,"text":"his delusion kicks in and says, it's not mother."}]},{"cues":[{"time":190000,"text":"Now, the most common interpretation of this,"},{"time":192000,"text":"which you find in all the psychiatry textbooks,"},{"time":194000,"text":"is a Freudian view, and that is that this chap --"},{"time":198000,"text":"and the same argument applies to women, by the way,"},{"time":200000,"text":"but I'll just talk about guys."},{"time":202000,"text":"When you're a little baby, a young baby,"},{"time":205000,"text":"you had a strong sexual attraction to your mother."},{"time":207000,"text":"This is the so-called Oedipus complex of Freud."},{"time":209000,"text":"I'm not saying I believe this,"},{"time":211000,"text":"but this is the standard Freudian view."},{"time":213000,"text":"And then, as you grow up, the cortex develops,"},{"time":216000,"text":"and inhibits these latent sexual urges towards your mother."},{"time":220000,"text":"Thank God, or you would all be sexually aroused when you saw your mother."},{"time":224000,"text":"And then what happens is,"},{"time":226000,"text":"there's a blow to your head, damaging the cortex,"},{"time":228000,"text":"allowing these latent sexual urges to emerge,"},{"time":232000,"text":"flaming to the surface, and suddenly and inexplicably"},{"time":235000,"text":"you find yourself being sexually aroused by your mother."},{"time":238000,"text":"And you say, \"My God, if this is my mom,"},{"time":240000,"text":"how come I'm being sexually turned on?"},{"time":242000,"text":"She's some other woman. She's an impostor.\""},{"time":244000,"text":"It's the only interpretation that makes sense to your damaged brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":248000,"text":"This has never made much sense to me, this argument."},{"time":251000,"text":"It's very ingenious, as all Freudian arguments are --"},{"time":254000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":256000,"text":"-- but didn't make much sense because I have seen the same delusion,"},{"time":261000,"text":"a patient having the same delusion, about his pet poodle."},{"time":263000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":264000,"text":"He'll say, \"Doctor, this is not Fifi. It looks exactly like Fifi,"},{"time":269000,"text":"but it's some other dog.\" Right?"},{"time":271000,"text":"Now, you try using the Freudian explanation there."},{"time":273000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":274000,"text":"You'll start talking about the latent bestiality in all humans,"},{"time":278000,"text":"or some such thing, which is quite absurd, of course."}]},{"cues":[{"time":281000,"text":"Now, what's really going on?"},{"time":283000,"text":"So, to explain this curious disorder,"},{"time":285000,"text":"we look at the structure and functions of the normal visual pathways in the brain."},{"time":289000,"text":"Normally, visual signals come in, into the eyeballs,"},{"time":292000,"text":"go to the visual areas in the brain."},{"time":294000,"text":"There are, in fact, 30 areas in the back of your brain concerned with just vision,"},{"time":297000,"text":"and after processing all that, the message goes to a small structure"},{"time":300000,"text":"called the fusiform gyrus, where you perceive faces."},{"time":305000,"text":"There are neurons there that are sensitive to faces."},{"time":307000,"text":"You can call it the face area of the brain, right?"},{"time":310000,"text":"I talked about that earlier."},{"time":312000,"text":"Now, when that area's damaged, you lose the ability to see faces, right?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":316000,"text":"But from that area, the message cascades"},{"time":319000,"text":"into a structure called the amygdala in the limbic system,"},{"time":322000,"text":"the emotional core of the brain,"},{"time":324000,"text":"and that structure, called the amygdala,"},{"time":326000,"text":"gauges the emotional significance of what you're looking at."},{"time":328000,"text":"Is it prey? Is it predator? Is it mate?"},{"time":332000,"text":"Or is it something absolutely trivial, like a piece of lint,"},{"time":334000,"text":"or a piece of chalk, or a -- I don't want to point to that, but --"},{"time":338000,"text":"or a shoe, or something like that? OK?"},{"time":340000,"text":"Which you can completely ignore."},{"time":342000,"text":"So if the amygdala is excited, and this is something important,"},{"time":345000,"text":"the messages then cascade into the autonomic nervous system."},{"time":348000,"text":"Your heart starts beating faster."},{"time":350000,"text":"You start sweating to dissipate the heat that you're going to"},{"time":353000,"text":"create from muscular exertion."},{"time":355000,"text":"And that's fortunate, because we can put two electrodes on your palm"},{"time":359000,"text":"and measure the change in skin resistance produced by sweating."},{"time":363000,"text":"So I can determine, when you're looking at something,"},{"time":365000,"text":"whether you're excited or whether you're aroused, or not, OK?"},{"time":369000,"text":"And I'll get to that in a minute."}]},{"cues":[{"time":371000,"text":"So my idea was, when this chap looks at an object, when he looks at his --"},{"time":375000,"text":"any object for that matter, it goes to the visual areas and,"},{"time":379000,"text":"however, and it's processed in the fusiform gyrus,"},{"time":382000,"text":"and you recognize it as a pea plant, or a table,"},{"time":385000,"text":"or your mother, for that matter, OK?"},{"time":387000,"text":"And then the message cascades into the amygdala,"},{"time":390000,"text":"and then goes down the autonomic nervous system."},{"time":392000,"text":"But maybe, in this chap, that wire that goes from the amygdala to the limbic system,"},{"time":397000,"text":"the emotional core of the brain, is cut by the accident."},{"time":400000,"text":"So because the fusiform is intact,"},{"time":402000,"text":"the chap can still recognize his mother,"},{"time":405000,"text":"and says, \"Oh yeah, this looks like my mother.\""},{"time":407000,"text":"But because the wire is cut to the emotional centers,"},{"time":410000,"text":"he says, \"But how come, if it's my mother, I don't experience a warmth?\""},{"time":414000,"text":"Or terror, as the case may be? Right?"},{"time":416000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":417000,"text":"And therefore, he says, \"How do I account for this inexplicable lack of emotions?"},{"time":423000,"text":"This can't be my mother."},{"time":425000,"text":"It's some strange woman pretending to be my mother.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":427000,"text":"How do you test this?"},{"time":429000,"text":"Well, what you do is, if you take any one of you here, and put you in front of a screen,"},{"time":431000,"text":"and measure your galvanic skin response,"},{"time":434000,"text":"and show pictures on the screen,"},{"time":436000,"text":"I can measure how you sweat when you see an object,"},{"time":439000,"text":"like a table or an umbrella. Of course, you don't sweat."},{"time":442000,"text":"If I show you a picture of a lion, or a tiger, or a pinup, you start sweating, right?"},{"time":447000,"text":"And, believe it or not, if I show you a picture of your mother --"},{"time":450000,"text":"I'm talking about normal people -- you start sweating."},{"time":452000,"text":"You don't even have to be Jewish."},{"time":454000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":456000,"text":"Now, what happens if you show this patient?"},{"time":460000,"text":"You take the patient and show him pictures on the screen"},{"time":464000,"text":"and measure his galvanic skin response."},{"time":466000,"text":"Tables and chairs and lint, nothing happens, as in normal people,"},{"time":471000,"text":"but when you show him a picture of his mother,"},{"time":473000,"text":"the galvanic skin response is flat."},{"time":475000,"text":"There's no emotional reaction to his mother,"},{"time":477000,"text":"because that wire going from the visual areas to the emotional centers is cut."},{"time":482000,"text":"So his vision is normal because the visual areas are normal,"},{"time":485000,"text":"his emotions are normal -- he'll laugh, he'll cry, so on and so forth --"},{"time":488000,"text":"but the wire from vision to emotions is cut"},{"time":491000,"text":"and therefore he has this delusion that his mother is an impostor."},{"time":494000,"text":"It's a lovely example of the sort of thing we do:"},{"time":497000,"text":"take a bizarre, seemingly incomprehensible, neural psychiatric syndrome"},{"time":501000,"text":"and say that the standard Freudian view is wrong,"},{"time":503000,"text":"that, in fact, you can come up with a precise explanation"},{"time":507000,"text":"in terms of the known neural anatomy of the brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":509000,"text":"By the way, if this patient then goes,"},{"time":511000,"text":"and mother phones from an adjacent room -- phones him --"},{"time":516000,"text":"and he picks up the phone, and he says, \"Wow, mom, how are you? Where are you?\""},{"time":520000,"text":"There's no delusion through the phone."},{"time":522000,"text":"Then, she approaches him after an hour, he says, \"Who are you?"},{"time":524000,"text":"You look just like my mother.\" OK?"},{"time":526000,"text":"The reason is there's a separate pathway"},{"time":528000,"text":"going from the hearing centers in the brain to the emotional centers,"},{"time":532000,"text":"and that's not been cut by the accident."},{"time":534000,"text":"So this explains why through the phone he recognizes his mother, no problem."},{"time":539000,"text":"When he sees her in person, he says it's an impostor."}]},{"cues":[{"time":542000,"text":"OK, how is all this complex circuitry set up in the brain?"},{"time":546000,"text":"Is it nature, genes, or is it nurture?"},{"time":549000,"text":"And we approach this problem"},{"time":551000,"text":"by considering another curious syndrome called phantom limb."},{"time":555000,"text":"And you all know what a phantom limb is."},{"time":557000,"text":"When an arm is amputated, or a leg is amputated, for gangrene,"},{"time":560000,"text":"or you lose it in war -- for example, in the Iraq war,"},{"time":562000,"text":"it's now a serious problem --"},{"time":564000,"text":"you continue to vividly feel the presence of that missing arm,"},{"time":568000,"text":"and that's called a phantom arm or a phantom leg."},{"time":571000,"text":"In fact, you can get a phantom with almost any part of the body."},{"time":573000,"text":"Believe it or not, even with internal viscera."},{"time":576000,"text":"I've had patients with the uterus removed -- hysterectomy --"},{"time":580000,"text":"who have a phantom uterus, including phantom menstrual cramps"},{"time":585000,"text":"at the appropriate time of the month."},{"time":587000,"text":"And in fact, one student asked me the other day,"},{"time":589000,"text":"\"Do they get phantom PMS?\""},{"time":591000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":592000,"text":"A subject ripe for scientific enquiry, but we haven't pursued that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":596000,"text":"OK, now the next question is,"},{"time":599000,"text":"what can you learn about phantom limbs by doing experiments?"},{"time":602000,"text":"One of the things we've found was,"},{"time":604000,"text":"about half the patients with phantom limbs"},{"time":606000,"text":"claim that they can move the phantom."},{"time":608000,"text":"It'll pat his brother on the shoulder,"},{"time":610000,"text":"it'll answer the phone when it rings, it'll wave goodbye."},{"time":612000,"text":"These are very compelling, vivid sensations."},{"time":615000,"text":"The patient's not delusional."},{"time":617000,"text":"He knows that the arm is not there,"},{"time":619000,"text":"but, nevertheless, it's a compelling sensory experience for the patient."},{"time":622000,"text":"But however, about half the patients, this doesn't happen."},{"time":625000,"text":"The phantom limb -- they'll say, \"But doctor, the phantom limb is paralyzed."},{"time":629000,"text":"It's fixed in a clenched spasm and it's excruciatingly painful."},{"time":632000,"text":"If only I could move it, maybe the pain will be relieved.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":635000,"text":"Now, why would a phantom limb be paralyzed?"},{"time":638000,"text":"It sounds like an oxymoron."},{"time":640000,"text":"But when we were looking at the case sheets, what we found was,"},{"time":643000,"text":"these people with the paralyzed phantom limbs,"},{"time":645000,"text":"the original arm was paralyzed because of the peripheral nerve injury."},{"time":649000,"text":"The actual nerve supplying the arm was severed,"},{"time":652000,"text":"was cut, by say, a motorcycle accident."},{"time":654000,"text":"So the patient had an actual arm, which is painful,"},{"time":657000,"text":"in a sling for a few months or a year, and then,"},{"time":661000,"text":"in a misguided attempt to get rid of the pain in the arm,"},{"time":664000,"text":"the surgeon amputates the arm,"},{"time":666000,"text":"and then you get a phantom arm with the same pains, right?"},{"time":670000,"text":"And this is a serious clinical problem."},{"time":672000,"text":"Patients become depressed."},{"time":674000,"text":"Some of them are driven to suicide, OK?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":676000,"text":"So, how do you treat this syndrome?"},{"time":678000,"text":"Now, why do you get a paralyzed phantom limb?"},{"time":680000,"text":"When I looked at the case sheet, I found that they had an actual arm,"},{"time":684000,"text":"and the nerves supplying the arm had been cut,"},{"time":687000,"text":"and the actual arm had been paralyzed,"},{"time":690000,"text":"and lying in a sling for several months before the amputation,"},{"time":694000,"text":"and this pain then gets carried over into the phantom itself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":700000,"text":"Why does this happen?"},{"time":702000,"text":"When the arm was intact, but paralyzed,"},{"time":704000,"text":"the brain sends commands to the arm, the front of the brain, saying, \"Move,\""},{"time":707000,"text":"but it's getting visual feedback saying, \"No.\""},{"time":709000,"text":"Move. No. Move. No. Move. No."},{"time":713000,"text":"And this gets wired into the circuitry of the brain,"},{"time":716000,"text":"and we call this learned paralysis, OK?"},{"time":719000,"text":"The brain learns, because of this Hebbian, associative link,"},{"time":723000,"text":"that the mere command to move the arm"},{"time":726000,"text":"creates a sensation of a paralyzed arm."},{"time":728000,"text":"And then, when you've amputated the arm,"},{"time":730000,"text":"this learned paralysis carries over into your body image"},{"time":734000,"text":"and into your phantom, OK?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":737000,"text":"Now, how do you help these patients?"},{"time":739000,"text":"How do you unlearn the learned paralysis,"},{"time":741000,"text":"so you can relieve him of this excruciating, clenching spasm"},{"time":745000,"text":"of the phantom arm?"},{"time":747000,"text":"Well, we said, what if you now send the command to the phantom,"},{"time":752000,"text":"but give him visual feedback that it's obeying his command, right?"},{"time":756000,"text":"Maybe you can relieve the phantom pain, the phantom cramp."},{"time":759000,"text":"How do you do that? Well, virtual reality."},{"time":761000,"text":"But that costs millions of dollars."},{"time":763000,"text":"So, I hit on a way of doing this for three dollars,"},{"time":766000,"text":"but don't tell my funding agencies."},{"time":768000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":769000,"text":"OK? What you do is you create what I call a mirror box."},{"time":773000,"text":"You have a cardboard box with a mirror in the middle,"},{"time":775000,"text":"and then you put the phantom -- so my first patient, Derek, came in."},{"time":779000,"text":"He had his arm amputated 10 years ago."},{"time":782000,"text":"He had a brachial avulsion, so the nerves were cut"},{"time":785000,"text":"and the arm was paralyzed, lying in a sling for a year, and then the arm was amputated."},{"time":789000,"text":"He had a phantom arm, excruciatingly painful, and he couldn't move it."},{"time":791000,"text":"It was a paralyzed phantom arm."}]},{"cues":[{"time":793000,"text":"So he came there, and I gave him a mirror like that, in a box,"},{"time":797000,"text":"which I call a mirror box, right?"},{"time":800000,"text":"And the patient puts his phantom left arm,"},{"time":803000,"text":"which is clenched and in spasm, on the left side of the mirror,"},{"time":805000,"text":"and the normal hand on the right side of the mirror,"},{"time":807000,"text":"and makes the same posture, the clenched posture,"},{"time":811000,"text":"and looks inside the mirror. And what does he experience?"},{"time":814000,"text":"He looks at the phantom being resurrected,"},{"time":817000,"text":"because he's looking at the reflection of the normal arm in the mirror,"},{"time":821000,"text":"and it looks like this phantom has been resurrected."},{"time":823000,"text":"\"Now,\" I said, \"now, look, wiggle your phantom --"},{"time":826000,"text":"your real fingers, or move your real fingers while looking in the mirror.\""},{"time":830000,"text":"He's going to get the visual impression that the phantom is moving, right?"},{"time":834000,"text":"That's obvious, but the astonishing thing is,"},{"time":836000,"text":"the patient then says, \"Oh my God, my phantom is moving again,"},{"time":839000,"text":"and the pain, the clenching spasm, is relieved.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":841000,"text":"And remember, my first patient who came in --"},{"time":844000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":845000,"text":"-- thank you. (Applause)"},{"time":849000,"text":"My first patient came in, and he looked in the mirror,"},{"time":852000,"text":"and I said, \"Look at your reflection of your phantom.\""},{"time":855000,"text":"And he started giggling, he says, \"I can see my phantom.\""},{"time":857000,"text":"But he's not stupid. He knows it's not real."},{"time":859000,"text":"He knows it's a mirror reflection,"},{"time":861000,"text":"but it's a vivid sensory experience."},{"time":863000,"text":"Now, I said, \"Move your normal hand and phantom.\""},{"time":866000,"text":"He said, \"Oh, I can't move my phantom. You know that. It's painful.\""},{"time":868000,"text":"I said, \"Move your normal hand.\""},{"time":870000,"text":"And he says, \"Oh my God, my phantom is moving again. I don't believe this!"},{"time":872000,"text":"And my pain is being relieved.\" OK?"},{"time":875000,"text":"And then I said, \"Close your eyes.\""},{"time":876000,"text":"He closes his eyes."},{"time":878000,"text":"\"And move your normal hand.\""},{"time":879000,"text":"\"Oh, nothing. It's clenched again.\""},{"time":880000,"text":"\"OK, open your eyes.\""},{"time":882000,"text":"\"Oh my God, oh my God, it's moving again!\""},{"time":883000,"text":"So, he was like a kid in a candy store."}]},{"cues":[{"time":885000,"text":"So, I said, OK, this proves my theory about learned paralysis"},{"time":890000,"text":"and the critical role of visual input,"},{"time":892000,"text":"but I'm not going to get a Nobel Prize"},{"time":894000,"text":"for getting somebody to move his phantom limb."},{"time":896000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":897000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":898000,"text":"It's a completely useless ability, if you think about it."},{"time":901000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":902000,"text":"But then I started realizing, maybe other kinds of paralysis"},{"time":906000,"text":"that you see in neurology, like stroke, focal dystonias --"},{"time":911000,"text":"there may be a learned component to this,"},{"time":913000,"text":"which you can overcome with the simple device of using a mirror."}]},{"cues":[{"time":916000,"text":"So, I said, \"Look, Derek\" --"},{"time":918000,"text":"well, first of all, the guy can't just go around carrying a mirror to alleviate his pain --"},{"time":921000,"text":"I said, \"Look, Derek, take it home and practice with it for a week or two."},{"time":925000,"text":"Maybe, after a period of practice,"},{"time":927000,"text":"you can dispense with the mirror, unlearn the paralysis,"},{"time":929000,"text":"and start moving your paralyzed arm,"},{"time":931000,"text":"and then, relieve yourself of pain.\""},{"time":933000,"text":"So he said OK, and he took it home."},{"time":935000,"text":"I said, \"Look, it's, after all, two dollars. Take it home.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":937000,"text":"So, he took it home, and after two weeks, he phones me,"},{"time":940000,"text":"and he said, \"Doctor, you're not going to believe this.\""},{"time":942000,"text":"I said, \"What?\""},{"time":943000,"text":"He said, \"It's gone.\""},{"time":945000,"text":"I said, \"What's gone?\""},{"time":946000,"text":"I thought maybe the mirror box was gone."},{"time":948000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":949000,"text":"He said, \"No, no, no, you know this phantom I've had for the last 10 years?"},{"time":952000,"text":"It's disappeared.\""},{"time":954000,"text":"And I said -- I got worried, I said, my God,"},{"time":956000,"text":"I mean I've changed this guy's body image,"},{"time":958000,"text":"what about human subjects, ethics and all of that?"},{"time":961000,"text":"And I said, \"Derek, does this bother you?\""},{"time":963000,"text":"He said, \"No, last three days, I've not had a phantom arm"},{"time":966000,"text":"and therefore no phantom elbow pain, no clenching,"},{"time":969000,"text":"no phantom forearm pain, all those pains are gone away."},{"time":972000,"text":"But the problem is I still have my phantom fingers dangling from the shoulder,"},{"time":976000,"text":"and your box doesn't reach.\""},{"time":978000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":979000,"text":"\"So, can you change the design and put it on my forehead,"},{"time":982000,"text":"so I can, you know, do this and eliminate my phantom fingers?\""},{"time":985000,"text":"He thought I was some kind of magician."}]},{"cues":[{"time":987000,"text":"Now, why does this happen?"},{"time":988000,"text":"It's because the brain is faced with tremendous sensory conflict."},{"time":991000,"text":"It's getting messages from vision saying the phantom is back."},{"time":994000,"text":"On the other hand, there's no proprioception,"},{"time":996000,"text":"muscle signals saying that there is no arm, right?"},{"time":1000000,"text":"And your motor command saying there is an arm,"},{"time":1002000,"text":"and, because of this conflict, the brain says, to hell with it,"},{"time":1005000,"text":"there is no phantom, there is no arm, right?"},{"time":1008000,"text":"It goes into a sort of denial -- it gates the signals."},{"time":1010000,"text":"And when the arm disappears, the bonus is, the pain disappears"},{"time":1014000,"text":"because you can't have disembodied pain floating out there, in space."},{"time":1018000,"text":"So, that's the bonus."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1020000,"text":"Now, this technique has been tried on dozens of patients"},{"time":1022000,"text":"by other groups in Helsinki,"},{"time":1024000,"text":"so it may prove to be valuable as a treatment for phantom pain,"},{"time":1027000,"text":"and indeed, people have tried it for stroke rehabilitation."},{"time":1029000,"text":"Stroke you normally think of as damage to the fibers,"},{"time":1032000,"text":"nothing you can do about it."},{"time":1034000,"text":"But, it turns out some component of stroke paralysis is also learned paralysis,"},{"time":1039000,"text":"and maybe that component can be overcome using mirrors."},{"time":1042000,"text":"This has also gone through clinical trials,"},{"time":1044000,"text":"helping lots and lots of patients."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1046000,"text":"OK, let me switch gears now to the third part of my talk,"},{"time":1050000,"text":"which is about another curious phenomenon called synesthesia."},{"time":1054000,"text":"This was discovered by Francis Galton in the nineteenth century."},{"time":1057000,"text":"He was a cousin of Charles Darwin."},{"time":1059000,"text":"He pointed out that certain people in the population,"},{"time":1061000,"text":"who are otherwise completely normal, had the following peculiarity:"},{"time":1065000,"text":"every time they see a number, it's colored."},{"time":1068000,"text":"Five is blue, seven is yellow, eight is chartreuse,"},{"time":1072000,"text":"nine is indigo, OK?"},{"time":1074000,"text":"Bear in mind, these people are completely normal in other respects."},{"time":1077000,"text":"Or C sharp -- sometimes, tones evoke color."},{"time":1080000,"text":"C sharp is blue, F sharp is green,"},{"time":1083000,"text":"another tone might be yellow, right?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1086000,"text":"Why does this happen?"},{"time":1088000,"text":"This is called synesthesia. Galton called it synesthesia,"},{"time":1090000,"text":"a mingling of the senses."},{"time":1092000,"text":"In us, all the senses are distinct."},{"time":1094000,"text":"These people muddle up their senses."},{"time":1096000,"text":"Why does this happen?"},{"time":1097000,"text":"One of the two aspects of this problem are very intriguing."},{"time":1099000,"text":"Synesthesia runs in families,"},{"time":1101000,"text":"so Galton said this is a hereditary basis, a genetic basis."},{"time":1104000,"text":"Secondly, synesthesia is about -- and this is what gets me to my point"},{"time":1108000,"text":"about the main theme of this lecture, which is about creativity --"},{"time":1111000,"text":"synesthesia is eight times more common among artists, poets, novelists"},{"time":1116000,"text":"and other creative people than in the general population."},{"time":1119000,"text":"Why would that be?"},{"time":1120000,"text":"I'm going to answer that question."},{"time":1122000,"text":"It's never been answered before."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1124000,"text":"OK, what is synesthesia? What causes it?"},{"time":1125000,"text":"Well, there are many theories."},{"time":1126000,"text":"One theory is they're just crazy."},{"time":1128000,"text":"Now, that's not really a scientific theory, so we can forget about it."},{"time":1131000,"text":"Another theory is they are acid junkies and potheads, right?"},{"time":1135000,"text":"Now, there may be some truth to this,"},{"time":1137000,"text":"because it's much more common here in the Bay Area than in San Diego."},{"time":1139000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":1140000,"text":"OK. Now, the third theory is that --"},{"time":1143000,"text":"well, let's ask ourselves what's really going on in synesthesia. All right?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1148000,"text":"So, we found that the color area and the number area"},{"time":1151000,"text":"are right next to each other in the brain, in the fusiform gyrus."},{"time":1154000,"text":"So we said, there's some accidental cross wiring"},{"time":1156000,"text":"between color and numbers in the brain."},{"time":1159000,"text":"So, every time you see a number, you see a corresponding color,"},{"time":1162000,"text":"and that's why you get synesthesia."},{"time":1164000,"text":"Now remember -- why does this happen?"},{"time":1166000,"text":"Why would there be crossed wires in some people?"},{"time":1168000,"text":"Remember I said it runs in families?"},{"time":1170000,"text":"That gives you the clue."},{"time":1172000,"text":"And that is, there is an abnormal gene,"},{"time":1174000,"text":"a mutation in the gene that causes this abnormal cross wiring."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1177000,"text":"In all of us, it turns out"},{"time":1179000,"text":"we are born with everything wired to everything else."},{"time":1183000,"text":"So, every brain region is wired to every other region,"},{"time":1186000,"text":"and these are trimmed down to create"},{"time":1188000,"text":"the characteristic modular architecture of the adult brain."},{"time":1191000,"text":"So, if there's a gene causing this trimming"},{"time":1193000,"text":"and if that gene mutates,"},{"time":1195000,"text":"then you get deficient trimming between adjacent brain areas."},{"time":1198000,"text":"And if it's between number and color, you get number-color synesthesia."},{"time":1201000,"text":"If it's between tone and color, you get tone-color synesthesia."},{"time":1204000,"text":"So far, so good."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1206000,"text":"Now, what if this gene is expressed everywhere in the brain,"},{"time":1208000,"text":"so everything is cross-connected?"},{"time":1209000,"text":"Well, think about what artists, novelists and poets have in common,"},{"time":1215000,"text":"the ability to engage in metaphorical thinking,"},{"time":1218000,"text":"linking seemingly unrelated ideas,"},{"time":1220000,"text":"such as, \"It is the east, and Juliet is the Sun.\""},{"time":1223000,"text":"Well, you don't say, Juliet is the sun,"},{"time":1225000,"text":"does that mean she's a glowing ball of fire?"},{"time":1227000,"text":"I mean, schizophrenics do that, but it's a different story, right?"},{"time":1230000,"text":"Normal people say, she's warm like the sun,"},{"time":1233000,"text":"she's radiant like the sun, she's nurturing like the sun."},{"time":1235000,"text":"Instantly, you've found the links."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1237000,"text":"Now, if you assume that this greater cross wiring"},{"time":1240000,"text":"and concepts are also in different parts of the brain,"},{"time":1243000,"text":"then it's going to create a greater propensity"},{"time":1246000,"text":"towards metaphorical thinking and creativity"},{"time":1249000,"text":"in people with synesthesia."},{"time":1251000,"text":"And, hence, the eight times more common incidence of synesthesia"},{"time":1254000,"text":"among poets, artists and novelists."},{"time":1256000,"text":"OK, it's a very phrenological view of synesthesia."},{"time":1259000,"text":"The last demonstration -- can I take one minute?"},{"time":1261000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1263000,"text":"OK. I'm going to show you that you're all synesthetes, but you're in denial about it."},{"time":1268000,"text":"Here's what I call Martian alphabet. Just like your alphabet,"},{"time":1272000,"text":"A is A, B is B, C is C."},{"time":1275000,"text":"Different shapes for different phonemes, right?"},{"time":1278000,"text":"Here, you've got Martian alphabet."},{"time":1280000,"text":"One of them is Kiki, one of them is Bouba."},{"time":1282000,"text":"Which one is Kiki and which one is Bouba?"},{"time":1284000,"text":"How many of you think that's Kiki and that's Bouba? Raise your hands."},{"time":1286000,"text":"Well, it's one or two mutants."},{"time":1288000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":1289000,"text":"How many of you think that's Bouba, that's Kiki? Raise your hands."},{"time":1291000,"text":"Ninety-nine percent of you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1293000,"text":"Now, none of you is a Martian. How did you do that?"},{"time":1295000,"text":"It's because you're all doing a cross-model synesthetic abstraction,"},{"time":1300000,"text":"meaning you're saying that that sharp inflection -- ki-ki,"},{"time":1304000,"text":"in your auditory cortex, the hair cells being excited -- Kiki,"},{"time":1309000,"text":"mimics the visual inflection, sudden inflection of that jagged shape."},{"time":1312000,"text":"Now, this is very important, because what it's telling you"},{"time":1315000,"text":"is your brain is engaging in a primitive --"},{"time":1317000,"text":"it's just -- it looks like a silly illusion,"},{"time":1319000,"text":"but these photons in your eye are doing this shape,"},{"time":1323000,"text":"and hair cells in your ear are exciting the auditory pattern,"},{"time":1326000,"text":"but the brain is able to extract the common denominator."},{"time":1331000,"text":"It's a primitive form of abstraction,"},{"time":1333000,"text":"and we now know this happens in the fusiform gyrus of the brain,"},{"time":1338000,"text":"because when that's damaged,"},{"time":1339000,"text":"these people lose the ability to engage in Bouba Kiki,"},{"time":1343000,"text":"but they also lose the ability to engage in metaphor."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1345000,"text":"If you ask this guy, what -- \"all that glitters is not gold,\""},{"time":1349000,"text":"what does that mean?\""},{"time":1351000,"text":"The patient says, \"Well, if it's metallic and shiny, it doesn't mean it's gold."},{"time":1353000,"text":"You have to measure its specific gravity, OK?\""},{"time":1356000,"text":"So, they completely miss the metaphorical meaning."},{"time":1359000,"text":"So, this area is about eight times the size in higher --"},{"time":1362000,"text":"especially in humans -- as in lower primates."},{"time":1365000,"text":"Something very interesting is going on here in the angular gyrus,"},{"time":1368000,"text":"because it's the crossroads between hearing, vision and touch,"},{"time":1371000,"text":"and it became enormous in humans. And something very interesting is going on."},{"time":1375000,"text":"And I think it's a basis of many uniquely human abilities"},{"time":1378000,"text":"like abstraction, metaphor and creativity."},{"time":1381000,"text":"All of these questions that philosophers have been studying for millennia,"},{"time":1384000,"text":"we scientists can begin to explore by doing brain imaging,"},{"time":1388000,"text":"and by studying patients and asking the right questions."},{"time":1390000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":1392000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":1393000,"text":"Sorry about that."},{"time":1394000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]}]}